                            <ul class="prev-next large"><li class="prev"><a href="http://lds.org/ensign/2010/11/temple-mirrors-of-eternity-a-testimony-of-family?lang=eng">Previous</a></li><li class="next"><a href="http://lds.org/ensign/2010/11/the-transforming-power-of-faith-and-character?lang=eng">Next</a></li></ul>
                            
                            
                            <h1>
                            Never Leave Him
                            </h1>
                            <h2 class="author">
                                    <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/neil-l-andersen?lang=eng"><div class="byline" id="">
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p2" class="">By Elder Neil&nbsp;L. Andersen</p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p3" class="">Of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles</p>
				</div></a>   
                                    </h2>
                            <hr>
                        </div><!-- end #details -->
                       
                        <div id="primary">
                            
                            <div class="audio-player">
                                        <div id="audioClose"><a href="#" title="Close Audio" onclick="closeAudioPlayer(); return false;">Close Audio</a></div>
                                    </div>
                            <blockquote class="intro dontHighlight">
                                        <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/neil-l-andersen?lang=eng">
                                                        <img id="talkPhoto" src="/bc/content/shared/content/images/leaders/neil-l-andersen-10.jpg" alt="Neil L. Andersen" class="img-decor">
                                                    </a>
                                        
                                        <div class="kicker" id="">As you choose not to be offended or ashamed, you will feel His love and approval. You will know that you are becoming more like Him.</div>
                                        
                                    </blockquote>
                            
                            <span style="display: none" id="article-id">09211_000_018</span>
				<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p5" class="">My beloved brothers and sisters across the world, I express my deep admiration for the faith and courage I see in your lives. We live in a most remarkable time&mdash;but a challenging time.</p>
				<div>
					<h2>The Lord Alerts Us to Dangers Ahead</h2>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p7" class="">The Lord has not left us alone in our quest to return to Him. Listen to His warning words alerting us to the dangers ahead: &ldquo;Take &hellip; heed, watch and pray.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote1-09211_000_018">1</a>
	</sup> &ldquo;Beware lest ye &hellip; be deceived.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote2-09211_000_018">2</a>
	</sup> &ldquo;Be watchful and careful.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote3-09211_000_018">3</a>
	</sup> &ldquo;Beware lest ye also &hellip; fall from your own stedfastness.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote4-09211_000_018">4</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p8" class="">No one of us is immune from the influences of the world. The Lord&rsquo;s counsel keeps us on guard.</p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p9" class="">You will remember Jesus&rsquo;s experience in Capernaum as disciples who had followed the Savior would not accept that He was the Son of God. The scripture reads, &ldquo;From that time many of his disciples &hellip; walked no more with him.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote5-09211_000_018">5</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p10" class="">Jesus then turned to the Twelve and asked, &ldquo;Will ye also go away?&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote6-09211_000_018">6</a>
	</sup></p>
				</div>
				<div>
					<h2>Will Ye Also Go Away?</h2>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p12" class="">In my own mind I have answered that question many times: &ldquo;Absolutely not! Not me! I will never leave Him! I am here forever!&rdquo; I know you have answered the same way.</p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p13" class="">But the question &ldquo;Will ye also go away?&rdquo; makes us think about our own vulnerability. Life is no spiritual picnic. The words of the Apostles from another setting come quietly into our mind: &ldquo;Lord, is it I?&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote7-09211_000_018">7</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p14" class="">We enter the waters of <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/study/topics/baptism?lang=eng">baptism</a> with joy and anticipation. The Savior beckons, &ldquo;Come unto me,&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote8-09211_000_018">8</a>
	</sup> and we respond, taking His name upon us. Not one of us wants this journey to be a brief flirtation with spirituality or even a notable but finite chapter. The road of discipleship is not for the spiritually faint of heart. Jesus said: &ldquo;Thou shalt love the Lord thy God with all thy heart, and with all thy soul, and with all thy mind.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote9-09211_000_018">9</a>
	</sup> &ldquo;Whosoever will come after me, let him deny himself, and take up his cross, and follow me.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote10-09211_000_018">10</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p15" class="">As we follow the Savior, without question there will be challenges that confront us. Approached with faith, these refining experiences bring a deeper conversion of the Savior&rsquo;s reality. Approached in a worldly way, these same experiences cloud our view and weaken our resolve. Some we love and admire slip from the strait and narrow path and &ldquo;[walk] no more with him.&rdquo;</p>
				</div>
				<div>
					<h2>How Do We Remain True?</h2>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p17" class="">How do we remain true to the Savior, His gospel, and the ordinances of His priesthood? How do we develop the faith and strength to never leave Him?</p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p18" class="">Jesus said, &ldquo;Except ye be converted, and become as little children, ye shall not enter into the kingdom of heaven.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote11-09211_000_018">11</a>
	</sup> We need the believing heart of a child.</p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p19" class="">Through the power of His Atonement, we are to become &ldquo;as a child, submissive, meek, humble, patient, full of love, willing to submit to all things which the Lord seeth fit to inflict upon [us], even as a child doth submit to his father.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote12-09211_000_018">12</a>
	</sup> This is the mighty change of heart.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote13-09211_000_018">13</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p20" class="">We soon see why a change of heart is necessary. Two words signal danger ahead: the words are <span class="emphasis">offended</span> and <span class="emphasis">ashamed.</span></p>
				</div>
				<div>
					<h2>Choose Not to Be Offended</h2>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p22" class="">To those troubled by the Savior&rsquo;s divinity, Jesus asked, &ldquo;Doth this offend you?&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote14-09211_000_018">14</a>
	</sup> In the parable of the sower, Jesus warned, &ldquo;He &hellip; [endureth] for a while: [but] when tribulation or persecution ariseth because of the word, by and by he is offended.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote15-09211_000_018">15</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p23" class="">Offense comes in many costumes and continually finds its way onstage. People we believe in disappoint us. We have unanticipated difficulties. Our life doesn&rsquo;t turn out exactly the way we were expecting. We make mistakes, feel unworthy, and worry about being forgiven. We wonder about a doctrinal issue. We learn of something spoken from a Church pulpit 150 years ago that bothers us. Our children are treated unfairly. We are ignored or underappreciated. It could be a hundred things, each very real to us at the time.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote16-09211_000_018">16</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p24" class="">In our weakened moments, the adversary seeks to steal our spiritual promises. If we are not watchful, our injured, childlike spirit will retreat back into the cold, dark crust of our former bloated ego, leaving behind the warm, healing light of the Savior.</p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p25" class="">When Parley&nbsp;P. Pratt, in 1835, was judged unfairly, bringing embarrassment and shame to him and his <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/ensign/2003/05/the-importance-of-the-family?lang=eng">family</a>, the Prophet <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/joseph-smith/">Joseph Smith</a> counseled, &ldquo;Parley, &hellip; walk such things under your feet &hellip; [and] God Almighty shall be with you.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote17-09211_000_018">17</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p26" class="">Another example: In 1830, Frederick&nbsp;G. Williams, a prominent medical doctor, was baptized. He immediately gave of his talents and prosperity to the Church. He became a leader in the Church. He donated property for the Kirtland Temple. In 1837, caught up in difficulties of the times, Frederick&nbsp;G. Williams made serious mistakes. The Lord declared in a revelation that &ldquo;in consequence of [his] transgressions [his] former standing [in the leadership of the Church had] been taken away from [him].&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote18-09211_000_018">18</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p27" class="">The beautiful lesson we learn from Frederick&nbsp;G. Williams is that &ldquo;whatever his personal weaknesses, he had the strength of character to [renew] his loyalty to the [Lord,] the Prophet and &hellip; to the Church, when it would have been so easy to have disintegrated in bitterness.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote19-09211_000_018">19</a>
	</sup> In the spring of 1840, he presented himself at a general conference, humbly asking <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/general-conference/2005/10/forgiveness?lang=eng">forgiveness</a> for his past conduct and expressing his determination to do the will of God in the future. His case was presented by Hyrum Smith, and he was freely forgiven. He died a faithful member of the Church.</p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p28" class="">I recently met the president of the Recife Brazil Temple, whose name is Frederick&nbsp;G. Williams. He recounted how his great-great-grandfather&rsquo;s decision of character had blessed the family and hundreds of his posterity.</p>
				</div>
				<div>
					<h2>Choose Not to Be Ashamed</h2>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p30" class=""><span class="emphasis">Offended</span> has a corrosive companion called <span class="emphasis">ashamed.</span></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p31" class="">In the Book of Mormon, we learn of Lehi&rsquo;s vision of the tree of life. The vision speaks of those noble souls who &ldquo;[pressed] forward through the mist of darkness, clinging to the rod of iron,&rdquo; arriving and &ldquo;[partaking] of the fruit of the tree.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote20-09211_000_018">20</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p32" class="">Nephi described the tree as &ldquo;<a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/general-conference/2009/10/the-love-of-god?lang=eng">the love of God</a>,&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote21-09211_000_018">21</a>
	</sup> bearing fruit that &ldquo;filled [the] soul with exceedingly great joy.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote22-09211_000_018">22</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p33" class="">After tasting of the fruit, Lehi saw &ldquo;a great and spacious building &hellip; filled with people &hellip; old and young, &hellip; male and female; and their &hellip; dress was exceedingly fine; and they were &hellip; mocking and pointing their fingers [of scorn] towards those who &hellip; were partaking of the fruit.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote23-09211_000_018">23</a>
	</sup> An angel explained that the mocking, the scoffing, the fingers of scorn represented the pride and wisdom of the world.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote24-09211_000_018">24</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p34" class="">Nephi declared plainly, &ldquo;We heeded them not.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote25-09211_000_018">25</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p35" class="">Sadly, there were others whose courage faltered. The scripture reads, &ldquo;<span class="emphasis">After</span> they had tasted of the fruit they were <span class="emphasis">ashamed,</span> because of those [who] were scoffing at them; and they fell away into forbidden paths and were lost.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote26-09211_000_018">26</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p36" class="">As disciples of <a class="no-link-style" href="http://jesuschrist.lds.org/">Christ</a>, we stand apart from the world. There may be times we feel uncomfortable as the fingers of scorn mock and dismiss what is sacred to us.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote27-09211_000_018">27</a>
	</sup> President <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/thomas-s-monson?lang=eng">Thomas&nbsp;S. Monson</a> warned, &ldquo;Unless the roots of your testimony are firmly planted, it will be difficult for you to withstand the ridicule of those who challenge your faith.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote28-09211_000_018">28</a>
	</sup> Nephi said, &ldquo;[Heed] them not.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote29-09211_000_018">29</a>
	</sup> Paul admonished, &ldquo;God hath not given us the spirit of fear; &hellip; Be not &hellip; ashamed of the testimony of our Lord.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote30-09211_000_018">30</a>
	</sup> We never leave Him.</p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p37" class="">While accompanying President <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/dieter-f-uchtdorf?lang=eng">Dieter&nbsp;F. Uchtdorf</a> to Eastern Europe last year, I marveled at the faith and courage of the Saints. One priesthood leader in Ukraine told us of being called to the branch presidency in the spring of 1994, only six months after his baptism. This would require becoming public with his faith and helping to register the Church in the city of Dnipropetrovs&rsquo;k. It was at a time of uncertainty in Ukraine, and openly showing faith in Christ and in the restored gospel could mean difficulty, including the possibility of losing his job as a pilot.</p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p38" class="">The priesthood leader told us, &ldquo;I prayed and prayed. I had a testimony, and I had made a covenant. I knew what the Lord wanted me to do.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote31-09211_000_018">31</a>
	</sup> Courageously, he and his wife went forward with faith, unashamed of the gospel of <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/jesus-christ">Jesus Christ</a>.</p>
				</div>
				<div>
					<h2>Where Much Is Given, Much Is Required</h2>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p40" class="">Some ask, &ldquo;Do I have to be so different from others?&rdquo; &ldquo;Can&rsquo;t I be a disciple of Christ without thinking so much about my behavior?&rdquo; &ldquo;Can&rsquo;t I love Christ without keeping the law of chastity?&rdquo; &ldquo;Can&rsquo;t I love Him and do what I want on Sunday?&rdquo; Jesus gave a simple answer: &ldquo;If ye love me, keep my commandments.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote32-09211_000_018">32</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p41" class="">Some ask, &ldquo;Aren&rsquo;t there many of other faiths who love Christ?&rdquo; Of course there are! However, as members of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, having a witness of His reality not only from the <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/topic/bible/">Bible</a> but also from the Book of Mormon; knowing His priesthood has been restored to the earth; having made sacred covenants to follow Him and received the gift of the Holy Ghost; having been endowed with power in His holy temple; and being part of preparing for His glorious return to the earth, we cannot compare what we are to be with those who have not yet received these truths. &ldquo;Unto whom much is given much is required.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote33-09211_000_018">33</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p42" class="">The Lord said, &ldquo;Thou mayest choose for thyself.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote34-09211_000_018">34</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p43" class="">I promise you, as you choose not to be offended or ashamed, you will feel His love and approval. You will know that you are becoming more like Him.<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote35-09211_000_018">35</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p44" class="">Will we understand everything? Of course not. We will put some issues on the shelf to be understood at a later time.</p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p45" class="">Will everything be fair? It will not. We will accept some things we cannot fix and forgive others when it hurts.</p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p46" class="">Will we feel separated on occasion from those around us? Absolutely.</p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p47" class="">Will we be astonished at times to see the anger a few feel toward the Lord&rsquo;s Church and their efforts to steal the struggling faith of the weak?<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote36-09211_000_018">36</a>
	</sup> Yes. But this will not deter the growth or destiny of the Church, nor need it impede the spiritual progress of each of us as disciples of the Lord Jesus Christ.</p>
				</div>
				<div>
					<h2>Never Leave Him</h2>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p49" class="">I love these words from a favorite <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/cm/display/0,17631,4650-1,00.html">hymn</a>:</p>
					<div class="figure">
						<div class="stanza" id="">
							<div class="line" id="">
		<span class="emphasis">The soul that on Jesus hath leaned for repose</span>
	      </div>
							<div class="line" id="">
		<span class="emphasis">I will not, I cannot, desert to his foes;</span>
	      </div>
							<div class="line" id="">
		<span class="emphasis">That soul, though all hell should endeavor to shake,</span>
	      </div>
							<div class="line" id="">
		<span class="emphasis">I&rsquo;ll never, no never, I&rsquo;ll never, no never,</span>
	      </div>
							<div class="line" id="">
		<span class="emphasis">I&rsquo;ll never, no never, no never forsake!</span>
		<sup class="noteMarker">
	      <a href="#footnote37-09211_000_018">37</a>
	    </sup>
	      </div>
						</div>
					</div>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p55" class="">Perfection does not come in this life, but we exercise faith in the Lord Jesus Christ and keep our covenants. President Monson has promised, &ldquo;Your testimony, when constantly nourished, will keep you safe.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote38-09211_000_018">38</a>
	</sup> We push our spiritual roots deep, feasting daily on the words of Christ in the scriptures. We trust in the words of living prophets, placed before us to show us the way. We pray and pray and listen to the quiet voice of the Holy Ghost that leads us along and speaks peace to our soul. Whatever challenges arise, we never, never leave Him.</p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p56" class="">The Savior asked His Apostles, &ldquo;Will ye also go away?&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote39-09211_000_018">39</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p57" class="">Peter answered:</p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p58" class="">&ldquo;Lord, to whom shall we go? thou hast the words of eternal life.</p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p59" class="">&ldquo;&hellip;&nbsp;We believe and are sure that thou art that Christ, the Son of the living God.&rdquo;<sup class="noteMarker">
	  <a href="#footnote40-09211_000_018">40</a>
	</sup></p>
					<p uri="/ensign/2010/11/never-leave-him.p60" class="">I too have that witness. I so testify in the name of Jesus Christ, amen.</p>
				</div>
			
                            
                            
